  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Install a Zipper Door Kit</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Clean and dry the plastic surface.</li>
    <li>Apply the zipper strips in the desired door shape.</li>
    <li>Press firmly to secure adhesion.</li>
    <li>Cut the plastic along the zipper opening.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Proper installation is key to long-term performance.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where Installations Go Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Poor Surface Preparation</h3>
  <p>
    Dirt or moisture reduces adhesive strength.
  </p>

  <h3>Misaligned Zippers</h3>
  <p>
    Leads to uneven opening and stress on the plastic.
  </p>

  <h3>Weak Adhesive Bond</h3>
  <p>
    Causes peeling over time, especially in heat.
  </p>

  <h3>Cutting Too Early</h3>
  <p>
    The adhesive should set before opening the door.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How It Fits Into a DIY Greenhouse Setup</h2>

  <p>
    A zipper door works alongside the frame, plastic covering, and ventilation system. A well-installed door improves usability without compromising structure.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is especially useful for temporary or seasonal greenhouses.
  </p>
</section>

